spanGrp.span: ‘There appeared a tiger with a child; something appeared and danced.
Jeska estee jiska (_) nãmã dugesãũ yaba yaba ra e-gla jirö dugesãũ klötiö-gẽ
Then it dances and the other one picks up a stick.
Jeska jeska í klötiö-gẽ kepanã jeska kal ke-gẽ-ka e-gla të
At that point the child gets in and and uh… what is it called?
Je nã je nã í të (_) yaba (_) pakkö-gẽ-wã yaba të je yaba të yaba të je je estee nẽ í kie-ite rö
He asked the other one once more to pick up the stick
Estee e-gla pakke-gẽ-nẽ etaba_gicha nẽ estee jirö (_) je kal kuga-nẽ
and then the tiger came out from within the branches and danced once more,
tögapa nãmã dugesãũ nãmã kal mẽ kaljula nã í klötiö-gẽ-nẽ etaba_gicha
but the other one came out again, the tiger did, when the others were dancing together.
nẽranã e-gla dugẽ estee dugesãũ-nẽ nãmã dugesãũ í klötiö-gẽ-ra í klötiö-gẽ ñara
Then uh… they went into the woods way up.
Kepa (_) kepanã ele í estee í í mĩ-gẽũ-lo-mĩ kabata nã í ku-gẽ-gãũ-lo
There the other one brings down ripe banans for him [the child]; he ate them.
Jeska e-gla të chomõ chomõli je jawẽ-gẽ të ĩã Ñe-gẽ-wã-ite
He pealed them but there were no ripe bananas;
jeska (_) í kwö ye/ estee kwöke-gẽ-sã'-ite-ra ka chomõli ta
the other one kept on bringing down bananas and gave them to him once more.
tögapa í të je chomõ/ e-gla të chomõ jawẽ/ jawẽ-gẽ-ite-ra nãjera ee chomõli mẽ-gẽ-nẽ-ite ĩã etaba_gicha
Next he went and threw himself into the river, he slipped into the river.
nẽranã í mĩ-gẽũ jẽk bu-gẽũ-mĩ diglö nã ra nã/ diglö nã/ í kulirjãr-gẽ-mĩ diglö nã
Then the child slipped down too.
When the other one fell down, he fell down on top of him.
Je kueinga jãr-gẽ-mĩ-ra-nã e-gla jãr-gẽ-te-nẽ í bata inga nẽ rã
he was going on the water and saw that the tiger was coming behind them;
í jũr-gẽ diglö inga (m) sũã-ite-ra-nã nãmã deu-ka-nẽ í töinga
so he pushed the other down into the river and he finally came out .’
Jeranã e-gla wötöe-gẽ-ite diglö nã Jeska í dugesãũ-nẽ dia kenẽga
